  "prompt": "Does a phone charger really stop charging when the phone is fully charged?",
  "response": "Modern smartphones and their chargers are designed with built-in protections to prevent overcharging, but the exact mechanism varies:\n\n1. Most modern devices have a charge management system that:\n- Reduces charging current when the battery is close to full\n- Switches to a \"trickle charge\" mode to maintain battery level\n- Stops drawing significant power once fully charged\n\n2. However, the charger may still draw a small amount of standby power even when the phone is fully charged, known as \"vampire\" or \"phantom\" power.\n\n3. Lithium-ion batteries (used in most smartphones) do not suffer from the \"memory effect\" like older battery types, so leaving them plugged in after full charge generally won't harm the battery.\n\n4. Some recommendations to preserve long-term battery health include:\n- Avoiding extreme temperatures\n- Not letting the battery consistently drop below 20%\n- Not always keeping the phone at 100% charge\n\n5. Some newer phones and chargers have more advanced power management systems that can more precisely control charging to reduce battery wear.\n\nSo while chargers do technically stop or significantly reduce charging when the phone is full, they're not completely disconnected from power.",
